snippet.textDisplay:
One of the reasons this trilogy felt so “Marvely” was the fact that there was little to no adult-related content. The original trilogy had cheeky jokes, sarcastic Han, and sparks of chemistry. These movies made it feel like we were watching children in adult bodies. There was no sexuality, real adult relationship conflict, or even normal adult reactions to trauma and stress.

The original Star Wars movies weren’t made for little children. Princess Leia’s slave bikini would NEVER be green-lit today! Kids ending up watching and enjoying the movies because their parents loved them, similar to how parents will share the Lord of the Rings trilogy with kids nowadays. Those movies aren’t made for kids, but kids can enjoy them and become lifelong fans.

I think I’ve just realized that these movies weren’t made for us... they were made for little kids. That’s why we have to suspend belief SO much, and probably why the people at Disney thought we could all overlook the massive plot holes, lost potential, and unbelievable character arcs.

I really appreciated your renewed take on The Last Jedi, because it’s precisely why I couldn’t stand the movie. It’s been so divisive in my family and friend group, though we all liked the exact same things about it. Narratively, it simply didn’t fit in the context of the second movie in a trilogy, and didn’t build off of anything in the first or set anything up for the third. Except for Rey and Kylo, which is why their scenes in this last movie were the only that felt cohesive and satisfying in the trilogy as a whole.

It’s really disappointing because they had a stellar cast and group of characters to work with. I think they were trying to do a Marvel thing by bringing in an outside director and letting him do his own thing, but it was completely inappropriate in the context of what works for adapting a collection of tonally diverse comics and what works for continuing an anthology of tonally consistent films.

snippet.textDisplay:
So I think this movie tried to do too much and tt seems like two or three movies in one. I noticed quite a few similarities with some aspects of episode 4, 5, and 6.

It also seemed that JJ Abrams spent a lot of time calling out the the Last Jedi-- Luke catching the light saber that he threw away on the previous movie, raising the xwing that was ignored on the last film, that Rey's parents weren't nobodies, that snook was some failed creation, etc.

The film started out strong, but suffered from pacing issues midway and toward the end, it seems like J.J didn't know how to end it, but I know he had lots of pressure placed on him.

I think the stars of this film for me has to be the chemistry between Finn and Poe, They deserved their own movie -- praying for a spin-off show or movie. Finn's crush on Rey was never addressed, but just used for a joke, and instead we got a forced kiss involving Kylo and Rey.

It's too bad that there was no consistent story throughout the trilogy and better development because in this film we see some potential in regards to character development that was only hinted at and never explored-- like I am curious how storm troopers break free of their brainwashing, etc.

snippet.textDisplay:
I completely agree with your comments on Disney listening to the fans and trying to appease them. On the surface, it's a sound strategy, but the problem with the Star Wars fanbase (at least the ones who complain loudest on the internet) is that they're downright schizophrenic; they don't know what the hell they want. Pre-Force Awakens, everyone hated George Lucas and the prequels and wanted something closer to the OT. Disney obliged and we got a movie that closely followed the beats of A New Hope. Then everyone said that had too much fan-service and they wanted something more original, so we got The Last Jedi, which largely did it's own thing and turned a lot of the themes of old-school Star Wars on their head. Everyone bitched again, because now it had wandered too far from the source material. So they went back to fan-service with Rise of Skywalker and (predictably) everyone's complaining again.

Working with your fans is admirable, but I don't think it's possible with this fanbase. Everyone in it has their own idea of what Star Wars "really is" and almost none of them match. Just look at the various fan-edits of the previous films. The Despecialized Editions, Star Wars Revisited, and SC38 Reimagined all have vastly different ideas on what these movies should be, and yet all three have been met with wide-spread support and acclaim. You can't intentionally appease a community like that.

Admittedly, I'm only recognizing this with the benefit of hindsight, but basing the plot of this new trilogy primarily around what they thought the SW community wanted was doomed to failure. I'm not saying to completely ignore the fans, but I think Disney would have definitely been better served creating a consistent narrative first. People would have still complained, but I suspect that the story would have been able to stand on it's own more effectively.

snippet.textDisplay:
I agree with you, Chris that the new trilogy lacks inner coherence. That's new to the Star Wars franchise, because so far Star Wars only had trouble connecting the different trilogies and other stories with each other so far:
1. Palpatine's return happens in the beloved Expanded Universe. It makes little sense there and it makes little sense here and undermines the events in Episode VI. The explanations are just paper-thin. But the fans loved the Dark Empire. And the Expanded Universe. But everyone for different reasons, while the fans of the movies didn't care for any of it as they do.
2. Nothing Obi-Wan Kenobi tells Luke in Episode IV is really shown in the Prequels and everyone has to argue to give validation to the claims that Obi-Wan and Anakin were good friends, Anakin wanted his son having his light saber and that Darth Vader killed Anakin. In fact during the movies the two were always in a fight, Anakin complained about Obi-wan holding him back, the light saber was never mentioned and Obi-Wan left a mortally wounded Anakin burning and slipping into lava to die.
Poor storytelling from Lucas
3. Although quite cool the ending of Rogue One doesn't fit at all with the beginning of Episode IV. Darth Vader just walks into the halls of Leia's ship without a light saber and without force killing anyone like before. Mabye he ran out of force juice? He just accuses Leia of having radio contact with the rebel fleet, which makes no sense, because her ship was around when the rebels attacked an empire planet.
4. There is more. But I'm getting tired. And I think I made a point.
All this is so painfully obvious that you realise that Star Wars lacks a road map for a very long time. Which is showing now, because Star Wars is the hands of people who are less qualified then George Lucas was. And there's a reason that he didn't made a new movie after Episode III.
Despite from all that nitpicking I enjoyed and enjoy ever Star Wars movie, including this one. Because I gave up on the idea that the storytelling is coherent. Once you do that and concentrate on the fun, adventure. space and light saber battles, the bizarre creatures, the different planets and the fight between good and evil, you are fine.

snippet.textDisplay: I saw the Force Awakens a couple times and never really felt that it jumped out of the screen at me, the story was not original, the visuals were eh and Rey was just a big Mary Sue. The Last Jedi made sequences from other films make no sense. Johnson took many liberties with the physics of Jedi and Spacecrafts. He introduced themes in the 8th movie of a franchise about the Skywalkers that were completely irrelevant. And it was an hour longer than it needed to be. It was the first time in a movie theater that I've almost fallen asleep. When I rewatched the movie on Netflix I saw the flaws in everything even clearer, example: throne room fight choreography. The only bad parts of Rise for me were the repetitive fan service, the constant jokes from C-3PO and the things Abrams kept in the background from TLJ. Abrams almost went overboard with the spectacle of this movie but still produced cohesive action scenes. Palpatine seemed rushed but it made sense by the power of his character and from the stance of the filmmaker. Kylo Ren had an incredible arch that concluded so well in this movie. The force energy and life force elements were so well done. It's one of my favorite star Wars movies already.
